<div id="review_3073430579" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3073430579" />
    <a title="Dawn F" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/14948447-dawn-f"><img alt="Dawn F" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1535435406p2/14948447.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3073430579?book_show_action=true">Jun 18, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Dawn F" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Dawn F" href="/user/show/14948447-dawn-f">Dawn F</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/14948447-dawn-f?shelf=loved">loved</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3073430579" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5906052843480990050">A while ago, going by the frankly disturbing subject matters Butler always seemed to circle around, I commented that I felt like she wrote in order to deal with issues, that it was therapeutic for her. Now I finally picked up this collection of short stories, essays and afterwords, and there it was in her own foreword. That’s exactly why she writes. If she has a phobia, she turns it into a story. If something is upsetting to her, she explores it by writing about it. Both because of that and the </span>
  <span id="freeText5906052843480990050" style="display:none">A while ago, going by the frankly disturbing subject matters Butler always seemed to circle around, I commented that I felt like she wrote in order to deal with issues, that it was therapeutic for her. Now I finally picked up this collection of short stories, essays and afterwords, and there it was in her own foreword. That’s exactly why she writes. If she has a phobia, she turns it into a story. If something is upsetting to her, she explores it by writing about it. Both because of that and the very personal reasons she states for writing the short stories she did, this quickly became one of my favorite works of her. Funny enough she finds writing short stories difficult, and yet I think she’s even better and sharper in her short stories than in longer fiction. Even her essays were gripping and fascinating, there wasn’t a word in this collection that wasn’t personal, honest or superfluous. I’m so glad I’d saved this collection for last, after having taken a break from her, because it once again cemented her as a brilliant mind and one of my favorite writers.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5906052843480990050" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


